5a.  Elaborative Interrogation.   Source: Pressley, Chapter 11.  Explanation:  As a  method used to improve the learning of facts, elaborative interrogation involves asking the student why questions on the material to be learned.  Research has shown that elaborative interrogation is effective and useful for learning information presented in list or expository passage form.  The questioning used in elaborative interrogation is hypothesized to work because it prompts the learner to activate prior knowledge and make links to the new information to be learned.  
<br>
5b.  Advanced Organizers:   Source:  Ausubel in Pressley, Chapter 11.  Explanation:  Advanced organizers are a type of instructional strategy that is used to improve both learning and comprehension.  Instruction using advanced organizers involves providing the student with headings, figures, or an outline prior to the actual material to be learned.  The advanced organizers not only signal important concepts to be learned, but also provide a structure or framework in which the individual can process the information.  Ausubel claimed that advanced organizers help students understand and remember new information, particularly reading passages containing new information.  
<br>
5c.  Multiple Ability Treatment.  Source:  Cohen  & Lotan (1995).  Explanation:  One of the two interventions used by Cohen and Lotan to alter the status processes in heterogeneous classrooms or groups.  Multiple ability treatment starts with a discussion by the teacher about how collective group tasks involve various types of intellectual abilities, that are not possessed by all members in the group.  It is stressed that different members of the group have some ability or competency in the different tasks that make up the collective group task.  
<br>
5d.  Assigning Competence:  Source:  Cohen  & Lotan (1995).  Explanation:  The other intervention used by Cohen and Lotan to equalize status in heterogeneous classrooms and promote the participation and achievement of lower-status students.  Assigning competence involves the teacher providing low status students with genuine and positive evaluations of their work or knowledge.  When the teacher provides the student with positive evaluations of their competencies in front of other students in the classroom or group and points out the relevance of those competencies to the work at hand, other students will also recognize that students ability and competence.  This raises the student's status in comparison to other students, increases his/her evaluations of self and abilities, and leads to an increase in classroom participation.  
<br>
6. Application:  
<br>
	I will be the teacher for a middle school geography classroom that is starting a lesson and group projects on different countries.  Students have been assigned to small groups.  The groups are heterogeneous in nature and were based on the teacher identifying the particular competencies of students and balancing groups based on these competencies.  The final project involves discussing the geography of the country, its history and culture, and its economic resources and exports.  
<br>
	Prior to dividing the students into groups, I would instruct the students on the use of advanced organizers as a strategy.  Students will practice using paragraph and chapter headings, keyword lists, and the graphs and figures in the text to predict what the reading will cover.  Students will also be encouraged to come up with why questions that might guide their reading, processing, and learning of the information (application of elaborative interrogation).  
<br>
	Each group will be provided with a short passage on their country.  As a group, they will have to come up with some questions that they want to answer in their presentation.  Students are encouraged to discuss their individual interests and abilities that they are bringing to the group (application of the multiple ability treatment).  I will facilitate this discussion by pointing out strengths and competencies that each of the members has demonstrated on either classroom lessons and tasks that parallel those needed for the current group project or on current contributions to the project.  Using examples of previous work will help in pointing out and assigning competencies to students who may not feel comfortable participating in the group (i.e. low status students).  By providing the group with evaluative positive feedback on the individual competencies of the group, the members will have greater confidence in their own abilities to contribute to the project and will help the group organize each individual's role on the project, distributing the leadership on the project (application of assigning competencies).  
<br>
	Once the group has determined who is responsible for what and have gathered resources, they will begin to put together the project.  Students will be expected to use advanced organizers provided in the resources they are using to organize the information and help facilitate the learning of the information by other members in their group.  The final presentation will involve a group presentation on the country, including handouts by the group that include key topics and information that the class should learn from the presentation.  The class (audience) will use this handout as an advanced organizers to understanding the material in the presentation.  The handout should also include why questions generated by the group  that will be used for discussion following the presentation.  Students in the audience are also encouraged to jot down questions for discussion during the presentation.  The questions should encourage the deeper processing of information by requiring students to consider prior knowledge gained in previous lessons and presentations in the geography class (application of elaborative interrogation).  

