<p>
5. Concept and Explanation Section
<br>
5a. Acedemic Engagement. Source: This idea was introduced in Chapter 11 of the Pressley text. Explanation: The process of encouraging a student to become "invested in and committed to learning, understanding, and mastering what is presented in school." This involves techniques such as providing authentic tasks, flexibility of pace and methods, and frequent occasions for students to ask questions. Engaged students are concerned with how well they are doing, and care about outcomes in addition to grades. They create new understandings for themselves rather than simply applying rote memorization. 
<p>
5b. Higher and Lower Order Teacher Questioning. Source: This idea was introduced in Chapter 11 of the Pressley text. Explanation: One way that educators can make a difference in a students education is to ask questions that determine the extent to which a concept or topic is understood. This can involve two types of questioning. Higher order questions are ones which require a "manipulation of information and reflection". These types of questions invoke a higher level of thinking and a deeper level of understanding than do lower order questions. Lower order questions only require simple recall of information which has been stored in a student's memory.
<p>
5c. Encourage Student Questions. Source: This idea was introduced in Chapter 11 of the Pressley text. Explanation: Just as it is useful for educators to ask students questions to ensure understanding, it is also important for students to ask questions of the teacher or other peers- especially when they do not understand or need clarification on a concept or topic.
<p>
5d. Mastery Learning. Source: This idea was introduced in Chapter 11 of the Pressley text. Explanation: In this type of learning program, course content is broken down into manageable units. The students learn one unit at a time by studying and taking quizzes on the material presented in that unit. In order to proceed to the next unit, a student must pass the current unit's exam at a high level of mastery, constituted by a score between 80% and 100%.
<p>
6. Applications Section
<br>
While in undergraduate school, I took a couple of what was known at that time as open learning courses. These types of courses were constructed as a type of "work at your own pace" class. The student was required to take quizzes and exams on one unit and then move on to the next if they had achieved a certain score. There was no actual lecture per se. Students could meet with the instructor on an individual basis during scheduled open learning lab hours.
<p>
I believe that this type of arrangement could be very applicable to the concepts I have chosen to highlight from the material presented in Chapter 11 of the Pressley text. If I were an instructor teaching a course in basic Psychology, I could offer the course as an open learning one. The course content would be broken down into units, which a student must master individually before moving onto a later unit. A student would be required to master the material presented in each individual unit and must demonstrate this by passing each quiz and exam with a score of 80% or better (5d).
<p>
On the road to mastering the material in each unit, it would be very advantageous for the student to meet with me during the scheduled open learning lab hours. During this time, I would attept to engage the student (5a) into the class and the material presented in it. This would be much easier to do in an open learning lab setting becuase since I would have the opportunity to meet with each student on an individual basis, I could then tailor the way I presented the material around the student. I would attempt to provide the student with authentic tasks that they found both interesting and challenging, in order for the student to create their own personal understanding, as opposed to rote memorization, of the material.
<p>
At this time, I would ask the student questions to evaluate their mastery of the material. Some of the questions I might pose to the idividual would be lower order ones such as "What discipline is Sigmund Freud associated with?", which would simply involve recalling that particular information which the student had previously memorized from the material presented in that unit. Other questions would be higher order ones such as "Compare and contrast the Psychoanalytic and Gestalt theories of learning." This type of question would require a much higher level of thinking and a much deeper level of understanding than would the lower order question example (5b).
<br>
 
<br>
In addition to posing higher and lower order questions to the student, I would also encourage the student to ask many questions of his or her own (5c). I would want the student to ask clarification questions any time s/he did not come to a level of full personal understanding of any concept or topic. In this way, I would hope to generate not only curiosity on the part of the student, but also provide an open and relaxed environment- one in which the student could feel comfortable and become invested in his or her education.
