5a.  Volunteers in the classroom.  Source:  Pressley.  Explanation:  Tutoring of students by volunteers increases the achievements of tutees.  Pressley says “the clear benefits of tutoring provided by volunteers should stimulate additional efforts to increase the use of volunteers in school” (Pressley, p. 261).

5b.  Reciprocal peer tutoring.  Source:  Pressley.  Explanation:  Students in a class are paired with one another, and are asked to help each other prepare for exams.  For example:  Before each exam, each student comes up with a short series of multiple-choice questions on the material, administers the questions to his/her partner, and explains the answer for each question that is answered incorrectly.  The process of generating the questions, taking the practice exam and explaining the content reinforces and deepens the learning, making this an effective approach.

5c.  Encouraging student questions.  Source:  Pressley.  Explanation:  When teachers encourage student questions, it can help students understand new material.  When teachers create an atmosphere that is comfortable for students to ask questions, they send a message to the class that asking questions is not a sign of low ability, but rather something a smart person does when he/she is in need of help.

5d.  Objectives as a directed learning device.  Source:  lecture.  Explanation:  Objectives help direct students’ attention to relevant information, when used under the appropriate circumstances (the learning of facts or simple concepts and principles) 


	I am teaching an introductory college-level journalistic writing course.  The course is structured with two exams to test factual information, and a series of journalistic writing assignments throughout the semester.  The course syllabus will include a series of objectives tied to each unit to help direct the students’ attention to the important information.  The content of the exams will closely follow the objectives.  
	To help the students prepare for the exams, they will be placed in a reciprocal peer tutoring situation.  The will be asked to write a brief exam, administer it to their partner, and discuss the answers to the questions before they take the exam I will administer.
	Student questions will be strongly encouraged -- for two reasons:  First, because it can help students understand the material, and second (and perhaps more importantly) because as budding journalists, asking questions is a very important part of their job.  I will provide frequent opportunities for students to ask questions by occasionally leaving gaps in the information I present to them and providing positive feedback to students who ask clarifying questions.  (Of course if no one asks the needed question to fill in the gap I will model the questioning process myself, and provide the needed information).
	I will also utilize the concepts of volunteers in the classroom by inviting local journalists from a variety of backgrounds to visit the classroom.  As we discuss magazine writing, for example, we might invite a writer from Meredith Corporation in Des Moines (the publisher of Better Homes and Gardens) to talk to the students about magazine writing and careers in magazine writing.  The volunteer would be invited back for the next class period to work with the students as they write their magazine stories, offering suggestions and ideas for improvement.

