5. Main Points

a. Amount of schooling influences academic competence (IQ).  [Ceci, 1991 in Pressley, p 254]  Newman (in Pressley) claims that the effect of schools are the ones that permit and foster a high degree of pupil engagement in learning.
Pupil engagement in learning:  Engaged students  are invested and committed to learning, understanding  and mastering what is presented in schools.  They concentrate on their work, are enthusiastic about work and are deeply interested in academic content.

Good schools lead students to acquire about academic issues, require integration of knowledge  and produce outcomes that carries a deeper meaning than the grade it results.
It presents the students with tasks they own, it involves them in decision-making about the curriculum and its assessments.

Engagement or Engaging Environments encourage risk-taking, respects students dignity and project a message that the student is important.  They should also be fun.

b. Teacher Questioning of Students about Academic Content. [Pressley, p259]
Questions a student experiences in school DO make a difference in learning.  Higher order questioning requiring manipulation of information and reflection and lower order questioning requiring simple recall of information  must be differentiated to understand and appreciate the effects of questioning on student learning.  Higher order questioning are important in high ability classes and lower order questioning may increase the likelihood that weaker classes will at least learn the facts.  Higher order questioning stimulates students to go beyond the facts, think through things and relate the new information to prior knowledge. 

c. Encouraging students Questions [Pressley, p260]:
Makes students understand that asking questions when uncertain is what smart people do when they are in need of assistance.  Teaching children how to ask questions about the content helps them to process it (courage 1989).

d. Teacher Expectancies [Pressley, p260]:
-Rosenthal and Jacobson found that teachers expectancies  of student achievement was a powerful determinant of actual achievement.  Pressley concludes it has only a small effect on student achievement.  Brody and Goode believe that differential treatments affects students perceptions of themselves and their own abilities.  

volunteers in the classrooms can strengthen school community relationships and increases achievement of tutees. 

6. First and second graders are in reading groups grouped according to reading levels.  Each student n the group is videotaped reading a book chosen by the teacher, but based on the skills from the reading assessments done previously by the teacher.  After this is completed, the child and the parent view the tapes at home together, discusses it and writes about what they likes and disliked about the reading materials and what they would like to do to improve the child's reading.  They are introduced to the fiction and non-fiction concepts and have been working on making predictions.  After some of the readings they make response booklets for these books.  In the response booklets they write and draw responses to the books they've been reading using prompts given by the teacher.

a. This lesson presents students with the task  they own.  It is seen as authentic to the students because it allows the student to assess their own reading abilities and skills.  Their responses to the material allows them to critique and contribute to the curriculum.  They decide what books they like and dislike.  Students may read better if they like the material, and thus obtain a higher achievement level. also if they feel they have some control over the learning process, they may enjoy learning more. 

b. The response booklets allows students to invent their own work and possibly contribute to the literary environment, therefore, they will be more engaged in the reading / language arts process.  Their contributions will enable students to internalize their importance in the learning process and possible raise achievement levels.

c. Children are questioned before and after stories on whether or not they are fiction or non-fiction after learning and understanding the difference between the two.  The students can explain  why it is fiction or non-fiction with the prompts  of higher level questioning because they must reflect on the content of the stories to know. This will help in assessing the levels of comprehension.  Lower level questions could be used to determine whether the students understood the basic facts in the story.  (great for non-fiction books).  





